# Prospector — Ideal Customer Profile (ICP)

_Last updated: (date) by (you or prospector)_

The prospector reads this before every run and qualifies the cartographer's
business directory against it. **This is where you define what you sell and to
whom.** Until you fill it in, the prospector has nothing to match — edit it by
hand. Keep it under ~150 lines.

## What you offer

- (e.g. websites + booking systems for service businesses)
- (one or two lines on the product/service you'd pitch these leads)

## Ideal customer (who's a lead)

- (e.g. independent restaurants and cafes without a working website)
- (e.g. trades — plumbers, electricians, landscapers — with no online booking)
- (e.g. tourism/lodging businesses in Camden & Rockport)
- Categories / OSM kinds that fit: (e.g. amenity=cafe, shop=*, craft=*)
- Towns to prioritize: (e.g. Rockland, Camden, Belfast)

## Disqualifiers (never a lead)

- National/regional chains (OSM brand tag) — they don't buy local.
- Businesses marked closed/unknown in the directory.
- (e.g. categories you can't serve, or that never convert)

## Fit scoring (0-1)

- 0.8-1.0: squarely in the ICP, clear unmet need, reachable.
- 0.5-0.7: plausible fit, some uncertainty (verify on the web before saving).
- < 0.5: don't save — leave it for a future, sharper ICP.

## Learned signals

(The prospector appends dated bullets here, each citing the feedback that drove
it — e.g. "2026-06-22: user starred a lead with no website → weight has_website
absence higher.")

## Standing instructions

- Discovery only — never contact a business or imply outreach.
- Prefer independent businesses with a website (reachable) over those without,
  unless an absent website is itself the opportunity you sell.
- Put the exact facts in save_find; keep the qualification reasoning in notes/.
- Walk the directory town by town; record coverage so runs don't repeat work.
